title: proposal for getOrSet
body:
over the years in my projects I've often needed this function

```
function getOrSet(obj,path,def){
    let ret = get(obj,path)
    if (ret!==undefined)
        return ret
    set(obj,path,def)
    return def
}
```

It is good when you want the default value to also persist in the object.
I was wondering if I'm missing something or, if popular, it would be good to have in lodash.

A similar repo exists
https://github.com/AndersDJohnson/lodash-get-or-set/blob/master/src/index.js
but I don't like it treating null equally to undefined.

title: Feature Request: unwind function.
body:
## 1) Design

```
Deconstructs an array field from the input objects to output a object for each element.
Each output object is the input object with the value of the array field replaced by the element.
@since version
@category Array
@param {array} The array of objects which you want to unwind.
@param {key} Key of object containing the array to be unwind.
```

## 2) Output

-   ### Basic

```
unwind([
    { name: 'Francisco', hobbies: ['Hacking', 'Ice skating'] },
    { name: 'Adelina', hobbies: ['Juggling', 'Graffiti', 'Painting'] },
], 'hobbies');
=> [
    { name: 'Francisco', hobbies: 'Hacking'},
    { name: 'Francisco', hobbies: 'Ice skating'},

    { name: 'Adelina', hobbies: 'Juggling'},
    { name: 'Adelina', hobbies: 'Graffiti'},
    { name: 'Adelina', hobbies: 'Painting'},
]
```

Inform us if you also want us to implement these ideas.

title: Proposal for convertArraystoObject function.
Better proposal of Array swap function.
body:
#4723 
1) Design

```
Swap two elements in an array
@since version
@category Array
@param {array} The array where the elements would be swapped.
@param {indexA} The index of the first element.
@param {indexB} The index of the second element.
```

## 2) Pseudo Code

    function swap(array, indexA, indexB){
        // Creating new array
        // Swapping the new array elements of indexA and indexB
        // Return new array
    }

## 3) Output

-   ### Basic

```
swap([1,2,3], 0, 1)
=> [2,1,3]

swap(['1','2','3'], 0, 1)
=> ['2','1','3']

swap([{k1:'v1'}, {k2:'v2'}, {k3:'v3'}], 0, 1)
=> [{k2:'v2'} , {k1:'v1'}, {k3:'v3'}]
```

-   ### Out of index

```
swap([1,2,3], 0, 4)
=> [1,2,3]
```

-   ### Misc

```
swap(undefined, indexA, indexB)
=> []
```

## 4) Test

-   ### Identity

Follows identity when indexA and indexB are identical

```
swap([1, 2, 3], 0, 0)
=> [1, 2, 3]
```

-   ### Commutative

Follows commutative when indexA and indexB are interchanged

```
swap([1, 2, 3], 0, 1)
=> [1, 2, 3]
swap([1, 2, 3], 1, 0)
=> [1, 2, 3]
```

-   ### Associative

Doesn't Follow associative

```
swap(swap([1, 2, 3], 0, 1), 1, 2)
=> [2, 3, 1]
swap(swap([1, 2, 3], 1, 2), 0, 1)
=> [3, 1, 2]
```

## 5) Quality

-   ### Data Immutability

```
Since in creating this function user data is not changed.
As we will create a new array of the given array.
Data Immutability of FP is followed.
```

## 6) Ideas

To create an object swap function which will swap the values of given object.

```
swap(object, keyA, keyB)
swap({ a: 1, b: 2}, 'a', 'b')
=> { a:2, b:1 }
```

Inform us if you also want us to implement these ideas.

title: sortedIndexBy, sortedIndexOf return incorrect results for mixed type arrays
body:
Given this array:
```
var array = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 'a', 'b', 'c'];
```

calling `sortedIndexOf` searching for `c` will return -1 instead of 7. 

```
_.sortedIndexOf(array, 'c');
> -1
````

Similarly:
```
_.sortedIndexBy([1, 2, 3, 4, 'a', 'b'], 'c');
> 0
```

This is an unfortunate side-effect of string to number comparison that happens in the `baseSortedIndexBy` function:
```
setLow = retHighest ? (computed <= value) : (computed < value)
```
https://github.com/lodash/lodash/blob/master/.internal/baseSortedIndexBy.js#L54

title: Feature request: a function to check if arrays intersects
body:
There is `intersection`, but nothing to check if arrays intersects.

A naive implementation would be `!_.isEmpty(_.intersection(...arrays))` but it can be inefficient for large arrays.

In spatial databases like PostGIS, beside [the intersection function](https://postgis.net/docs/manual-3.0/ST_Intersection.html), there is [an intersects function](https://postgis.net/docs/manual-3.0/ST_Intersects.html).

title: groupBy incorrect behaviour
body:
Hello,
String numbers as object keys treated incorrectly

Input
```
[
  {question: 'mutual'},
  {question: 'Question'},
  {question: 'One question'},
  {question: 'htllo'},
  {question: '1'},
  {question: 'message'},
  {question: 'mutual'}
];
```

**Expected output**
```
{
      'mutual': [ { question: 'mutual' }, { question: 'mutual' } ],
      Question: [ { question: 'Question' } ],
      'One question': [ { question: 'One question' } ],
      htllo: [ { question: 'htllo' } ],
      '1': [ { question: '1' } ],
      message: [ { question: 'message' } ]
}
```

**Current output**
```
{
      '1': [ { question: '1' } ],
      'mutual': [ { question: 'mutual' }, { question: 'mutual' } ],
      Question: [ { question: 'Question' } ],
      'One question': [ { question: 'One question' } ],

}
```

```js
const { isPlainObject, mapKeys, mapValues } = require('lodash/fp');

const mapKeysDeep = cb => obj =>
  Array.isArray(obj)
    ? obj.map(mapKeysDeep(cb))
    : isPlainObject(obj)
      ? mapValues(mapKeysDeep(cb))(mapKeys(cb)(obj))

module.exports = mapKeysDeep;
```

title: [templates] remove empty new lines ("newline slurp")
body:
How can I remove the empty newlines produces by control-flow statements? It seems that lodash doesn't support `-%>` or anything equivalent.
As an example,

```js
const _ = require('lodash')

const template = `%files
/usr/bin/<%= name %>
<% if (_.isObject(icon)) { %>
<% _.forEach(icon, function (path, resolution) { %>
/usr/share/icons/<%= resolution %>/apps/<%= name %>.png
<% }) } else { %>/usr/share/pixmaps/<%= name %>.png<% } %>

More text`

const data = { name: 'lodash', icon: { '16x16': 'lodash16.png', '32x32': 'lodash32.png' } }
_.template(template)(data)
```

The previous code will output :

```
%files
/usr/bin/lodash


/usr/share/icons/16x16/apps/lodash.png

/usr/share/icons/32x32/apps/lodash.png


More text
```

but what I would like to see is:

```
%files
/usr/bin/lodash
/usr/share/icons/16x16/apps/lodash.png
/usr/share/icons/32x32/apps/lodash.png

More text
```

title: _.isEmpty(false) should return false, but returns true
body:
`_.isEmpty(false)` should return `false`, but returns `true`.

`false` is not a empty value.

`null` can be a empty value. `undefined` can be a empty value. But false is a not a empty value.

Thanks

title: It seems _.intersectionBy and intersectionWith has wrong behavior.
body:
Hi Folks,
I was trying intersectionWith to find the items in two array with same semantics. The intersectionBy/With does not return all intersect but only the first value based on response.

Following is the simple case to reproduce unexpected behavior (Or may be i misunderstood, in that case better to update example in doc with following.)

Actual:
```
_.intersectionBy([1.2, 1.3, 3.3, 3.1], [1.2, 2.2], Math.floor)
> [1.2]
_.intersectionBy([1.2, 1.3, 3.3, 3.1], [1.3, 2.2], Math.floor)
> [1.2]
_.intersectionWith([1.2, 1.3, 3.3, 3.1], [1.3, 2.2], (a, b) => Math.floor(a) === Math.floor(b));
> [1.2]
```

Expected ??

```
_.intersectionBy([1.2, 1.3, 3.3, 3.1], [1.2, 2.2], Math.floor)
> [1.2, 1.3]
_.intersectionBy([1.2, 1.3, 3.3, 3.1], [1.3, 2.2], Math.floor)
> [1.2, 1.3]
_.intersectionWith([1.2, 1.3, 3.3, 3.1], [1.3, 2.2], (a, b) => Math.floor(a) === Math.floor(b));
> [1.2, 1.3]
```

I was expecting its behavior similar to diffferenceWith :) 
Actual:
```
_.differenceBy([1.2, 1.3, 3.3, 3.1], [1.2, 2.2], Math.floor)
> [3.3, 3.1]
```

title: Which git branch should be based on when submitting a pull request
body:
Hi, I'd eventually like to contribute in some way but I encountered a problem.

## Brief of question
This is my first time participating in open source work. So I searched for the correct way to submit a PR. Then I found the most appropriate path forward would be to fork, test, and build out of one git branch(e.g. the `master` branch). But after reading the [CONTRIBUTING.md](https://github.com/lodash/lodash/blob/master/.github/CONTRIBUTING.md), 
**I was confused about which git branch should I commit to: `master` or `4.17.15-post`**.


## The ways I had tried to solve this problem:

1. Read  [CONTRIBUTING.md](https://github.com/lodash/lodash/blob/master/.github/CONTRIBUTING.md)
 In the `Contributing to Lodash` section I found:
> Contributions are always welcome. Before contributing please read the code of conduct & search the issue tracker; your issue may have already been discussed or fixed in `master`. To contribute, fork Lodash, commit your changes, & send a pull request.

It seems like I should checkout a new branch based `master`, but then I found that in the section  `Pull request`:

> For additions or bug fixes you should only need to modify lodash.js. Include updated unit tests in the test directory as part of your pull request. 
 ...
 Before running the unit tests you’ll need to install, npm i, development dependencies. Run unit tests from the command-line via npm test, or open test/index.html & test/fp.html in a web browser. 

I didn't find `lodash.js` under the `master` branch, and `npm run test` also didn't work because of the lack of files needed for building and testing.
But I found the `lodash.js` under the `4.17.15-post` branch,  and `npm run test` could work .

So, if I want to fix a bug, should I develop based on the `4.17.15-post` branch?

Then I found the following paragraph in the `Notice` section:
> Pardon the mess. The master branch is in flux while we work on Lodash v5. This means things like npm scripts, which we encourage using for contributions, may not be working. Thank you for your patience.

Does this mean contributions should not commit to the master branch  for now?

2. Search recent pull requests
To figure it out, I checked some recent pull requests, and found that some were commited based on the `master` branch ([PR#4681](https://github.com/lodash/lodash/pull/4681)), and some were commited based on `4.17.15-post` branch ([PR#4515](https://github.com/lodash/lodash/pull/4515)), so I was  completly confused:

## Detail of  question
1. If I want to fix a bug, which branch should be used for development?

2. If I only modify a document file like `REAMDE.md` or `CONTRIBUTING.md`, which branch should be used to submit?

**Hope someone can help.**
